§ 5. Arabiton] Diodorus calls them Ἀρβΐται, Strabo Ἀρβιες, Arrian Ἀραβ ται m his Anabasis, Ἀράβιες in his Indian history. Their further or western boundary was the river variously called Ἀρβις, Ἀράβιος, Ἀράβις and Arabus. Beyond this river lay the Oritae, and beyond them again the Gedrosii Gadi-osii or Kedrosii. The words inde ...... Cedrosmrmn are obviously wrong. But, as has been already observed by Vogel. they may very well for all that have been written by Curtius himself, for Diodorus speaks of the submission of τοὺς τὴν Κεδρωσίαν οἰκοῦντας immediately after that of the Arbhae, and then goes on to mention the Oritae, returning further on to the march through Κεδρωσία, as Curtius does below. They probably both followed the same authorities, in which there may have been some confusion to account for their strange muddle.
